<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-513-206  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 513 206.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Personal Computing  June 29 1990 v14 n6 p129(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Can you trust your database? (database audits can find errorsbefore they find you)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Liskin, Miriam.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Data base integrity should not be taken for granted, especially inthe corporate environment where mistakes could be costly for thewhole company.andP;  Data base users need to make sure their softwareis doing its job accurately: storing, retrieving, deleting,performing calculations correctly, and printing the correctrecords in the right order on reports and lists.andP;  A data baseaudit is useful, but must be developed and run by the usersthemselves in conjunction with the programming staff.andP;  A two partapproach is necessary: examining the data itself for validity andverifying that data entry forms, reports, queries, batchprocesses, file maintenance procedures and custom programs areperforming properly.andP;  One method is to run a new data base systemin parallel with the manual system it is meant to replace.andP;  Thismethod can uncover gaps in the computerized application.andP;  Aduplicate records check and verification of system rejection ofduplicates is an essential but often overlooked way to checkvalidity.andP;  Another way to audit the data base is to check formismatched data using procedures different from the normalprocessing sequence.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Data Base AdministrationData IntegrityValidationAuditing of Computer Systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Designing a test data file. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>